Rep. Sykes has strongly pushed back on Republican attempts to cut Medicaid, SNAP, and ACA coverage and has implored her colleagues to work across the aisle to put together a budget that lowers costs, improves opportunity, and expands access to health care.

In Ohio alone, the Republicans' reconciliation bill will kick 489,815 people off their health care; will put nearly 100,000 people at risk of going hungry; is likely to close 11 rural hospitals and 1 in 4 nursing homes; will eliminate 37,000 manufacturing jobs; and will raise energy costs for families by $410.

Throughout her life, Truth tirelessly fought against slavery, racism, and inequality. During the Civil War, she aided the Union cause, helping recruit Black troops and advocating for freed slaves. Her iconic words continue to dare women to challenge the status quo and fight for a more just and equitable world for everyone, no matter their gender, race, sexuality, or creed. Akron’s newest landmark, the Sojourner Truth Legacy Plaza, was unveiled on May 29, 2024, the 173rd anniversary of Truth’s “Ain’t I a Woman?” speech.

Sojourner Truth, born Isabella Baumfree, was a powerful voice for abolitionism and women’s rights. She gave her infamous speech, “Ain’t I a Woman,” in Akron at the 1951 Women’s Rights Convention. She spoke about injustices she and the women around her experienced and would continue to face into the future.
